Below is a **complete, self‑contained binding** that shows one idiomatic way to expose the C++ iterator of *libpcapng* to OCaml.  
It contains

* the public OCaml interface (`pcapng.mli`);
* the C‑stub implementation (`pcapng_stubs.c`);
* a tiny “glue” header (`pcapng_wrapper.hpp`) that adapts the C++ library to the C‑API.

You can drop the three files into a directory, add a `dune` stanza (or a classic `Makefile`) and compile them with the usual OCaml/ocamlc‐opt command line.  
Everything needed to understand the design is inside the comment blocks.

---

## 1.  OCaml public interface – **`pcapng.mli`**

```ocaml
(** {1 libpcapng OCaml bindings} *)

(** A handle to an opened pcapng file.  The value is opaque – it is
    managed by the C stub and will be automatically released when it
    is garbage‑collected. *)
type capture

(** A single captured frame.  Only a subset of the information that
    libpcapng can provide is exposed – enough for most analysis tools. *)
type frame = {
  ts_sec   : int;          (** Timestamp, seconds since the epoch *)
  ts_usec  : int;          (** Micro‑seconds part of the timestamp *)
  data     : bytes;       (** Raw packet bytes (may be empty) *)
}

(** Exception raised when the file cannot be opened or when the
    underlying library reports an error. *)
exception Error of string

(** [open_file name] opens a pcapng file for reading.  The returned
    [capture] must be closed with {!close} (or will be closed
    automatically when the value is reclaimed). *)
val open_file : string -> capture

(** Close the file explicitly.  After this call the [capture] must not
    be used again.  This is a no‑op if the handle is already closed. *)
val close : capture -> unit

(** Iterate over all frames in the file, invoking the supplied OCaml
    function for each frame.

    The iteration is performed in C++ (i.e. on the same thread that
    called [iter]) and the callback is invoked for each frame.  If the
    callback raises an exception, iteration stops and the exception is
    propagated to the caller of [iter].

    The callback receives a freshly allocated [frame] record – the
    callback is free to keep or discard it. *)
val iter : capture -> (frame -> unit) -> unit

(** A convenience function that collects all frames into a list.
    It is *not* recommended for very large captures because it holds
    everything in memory.  It is provided mainly for testing. *)
val to_list : capture -> frame list
```

### Design notes

* **Opaque handle** – the `capture` type is a custom block that stores a
  pointer to a C++ `PcapNgReader`.  The block has a finaliser that calls
  `delete` on the C++ object, so the user never has to manage the memory
  manually.
* **Callback style** – `iter` receives an OCaml closure.  The stub loops
  over the C++ iterator and calls `caml_callback` for each frame.  This
  is the most natural API for OCaml users (it mirrors `Array.iter`,
  `List.iter`, …) and avoids the need for a “pull” style iterator that
  would require the user to write a more cumbersome loop.
* **Exception handling** – any error from the C++ side is turned into the
  OCaml exception `Error`.  If the user‑provided callback raises, the
  exception bubbles up and the iteration stops immediately.
* **Memory safety** – each frame’s payload is copied into an OCaml
  `bytes` value.  No pointer to the C++ buffer is ever handed to OCaml,
  so the GC cannot corrupt the native memory.  The copy is cheap compared
  with the cost of parsing a pcapng file.

