## 2.  C++/C glue – **`pcapng_wrapper.hpp`**

```cpp
/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   Small wrapper that hides the real libpcapng C++ API behind a tiny C‑API.
   The real libpcapng library is assumed to provide a class `PcapNgReader`
   with the following (simplified) interface:

       class PcapNgReader {
       public:
           explicit PcapNgReader(const std::string &filename);
           ~PcapNgReader();

           // Returns true and fills `out` if a frame is available,
           // false when EOF is reached.
           bool next_frame(Frame &out);
       };

       struct Frame {
           uint32_t ts_sec;   // seconds part of timestamp
           uint32_t ts_usec;  // micro‑seconds part
           const uint8_t *data;
           size_t        length;
       };

   The wrapper below only forwards these calls; it is placed in its own
   header so that the C stub can be compiled as a C++ file without
   pulling the entire libpcapng headers into the OCaml world.
----------------------------------------------------------------------- */

#ifndef PCAPNG_WRAPPER_HPP
#define PCAPNG_WRAPPER_HPP

#include <string>
#include <stdexcept>
#include <cstddef>
#include <cstdint>

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   The real libpcapng headers are not shipped with this example, so we
   provide a minimal mock‑up.  Replace the following `#include` and the
   definitions of `PcapNgReader`/`Frame` with the real ones when you
   integrate the binding with the actual library.
--------------------------------------------------------------------- */
#include "libpcapng_mock.hpp"   // <-- replace with the real header

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Helper: translate any C++ exception into an OCaml RuntimeError.
   The stub code calls `translate_cpp_exception()` before returning to
   OCaml.
--------------------------------------------------------------------- */
inline void translate_cpp_exception()
{
    try {
        throw;      // re‑throw the current exception
    } catch (const std::exception &e) {
        // The stub will convert this to an OCaml exception.
        // We just store the message in a static buffer because the
        // OCaml side will copy it immediately.
        static std::string msg;
        msg = e.what();
        // The stub will read `msg.c_str()` via `caml_raise_failure`.
        // (The stub is the only place that calls this function.)
    } catch (...) {
        // Unknown exception – use a generic message.
        static const char unknown[] = "unknown C++ exception";
        // The stub will use this string.
    }
}

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   The opaque type that lives inside the OCaml custom block.
--------------------------------------------------------------------- */
struct caml_pcapng_reader {
    PcapNgReader *reader;   // owned; deleted by the finaliser
};

#endif /* PCAPNG_WRAPPER_HPP */
```

> **NOTE** – The file `libpcapng_mock.hpp` is only a placeholder for the real
> libpcapng header.  When you compile the binding against the actual library,
> replace the `#include "libpcapng_mock.hpp"` line with the proper header (e.g.
> `#include <pcapng.hpp>`).  The mock header is omitted here to keep the
> example focused on the binding logic.

