## 4.  How to compile & link

```bash
# 1. Compile the C++ stub (needs a C++ compiler)
g++ -c -std=c++11 -I$(ocamlc -where) -I/path/to/libpcapng/include \
    -fPIC pcapng_stubs.c -o pcapng_stubs.o

# 2. Build a shared library that OCaml can dlopen
g++ -shared -o libpcapng_stubs.so pcapng_stubs.o -L/path/to/libpcapng/lib -lpcapng

# 3. Compile the OCaml code (assuming pcapng.ml uses the .mli)
ocamlopt -c pcapng.ml
ocamlopt -c main.ml                # your program
ocamlopt -o my_program pcapng.cmx main.cmx \
    -cclib -L. -cclib -lpcapng_stubs
```

If you are using **Dune**, the stanza is roughly:

```dune
(executable
 (name main)
 (modules main pcapng)
 (libraries ctypes)
 (c_names pcapng_stubs)
 (cflags (:standard -I$(ocaml_where) -I/path/to/libpcapng/include))
 (link_flags -L/path/to/libpcapng/lib -lpcapng))
```

Make sure the generated `libpcapng_stubs.so` is on the runtime library path
(`LD_LIBRARY_PATH` on Linux, `DYLD_LIBRARY_PATH` on macOS) or install it in a
standard location.

---

## 5.  Minimal example of OCaml usage

```ocaml
(* main.ml ----------------------------------------------------------- *)
let () =
  (* Register the custom exception (once per process) *)
  let _ = Callback.register_exception "Pcapng.Error" (Pcapng.Error "") in
  let cap = Pcapng.open_file "sample.pcapng" in
  (* Print every frame's length *)
  Pcapng.iter cap (fun f ->
      Printf.printf "frame: %d bytes, ts=%d.%06d\n"
        (Bytes.length f.Pcapng.data) f.Pcapng.ts_sec f.Pcapng.ts_usec);
  Pcapng.close cap
```

Running this program will walk the file, invoking the OCaml closure for each
frame, exactly as requested.

---

### TL;DR – What you get

* **`type capture`** – an opaque handle with automatic finalisation.
* **`iter : capture -> (frame -> unit) -> unit`** – the idiomatic OCaml
  iterator that runs user code for each frame.
* Full error handling via the `Pcapng.Error` exception.
* No unsafe pointer exposure; each frame is safely copied into an OCaml
  `bytes` value.

You can now ship the three files (`pcapng.mli`, `pcapng_wrapper.hpp`,
`pcapng_stubs.c`) as the complete binding for libpcapng.  Adjust the
`#include` in `pcapng_wrapper.hpp` to point at the real libpcapng headers,
and you are ready to go. Happy hacking!
